&gt; What benefit does org.junit.Assert provide, as opposed to 
&gt; junit.framework.Assert? Unless some new assertions are available - 
&gt; Assert#assertException or Assert#assertInstanceOf, for 
&gt; example - I don&#39;t 
&gt; think the introduction of a new class is justified on the basis of 
&gt; altering which Exception it uses to indicate a failed assertion.
&gt; 
&gt; Elliotte Harold wrote:
&gt; &gt; Alexandru Popescu wrote:
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt;&gt;As far as I can tell I think that the new Assert class was 
&gt; created to remove the custom 
&gt; &gt;&gt;AssertionException and use the AssertionException provided 
&gt; since JDK1.4. From my point of view this 
&gt; &gt;&gt;is definitely a very good reason to have it.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; OK. I can see that, but I think that&#39;s a very bad idea. A JUnit 
&gt; &gt; assertion test failure is not at all the same thing as a 
&gt; Java language 
&gt; &gt; assert failure. They are two different things and they should be 
&gt; &gt; distinguishable. Failure to do that might cause unexpected 
&gt; problems with 
&gt; &gt; various tools that interpret an AssertionError as meaning 
&gt; one thing when 
&gt; &gt; JUnit makes it mean something different.
